MSstatsTMT_2025_09_v3.1.4

Stephanie Huang

2025-09-11-12

Checking PD 2.4’s As Batch Function.

Note: Renamed to 2025_09_22_v3.1.4_PD2.4_as_batch_check.html & sent to Thermo on 2025-09-22

Background Information

This is a part of the re-analysis of my EE-exp LCMS data (96 raw files) collected from 2021-2022 for my PhD write-up (2025-08 to 2025-09). In this re-analysis series, I tested different UniProt databases/FASTAs in PD2.4, including using the UniProt rat reference proteome (1 protein sequence per gene 1pspg - 22400s), Swiss-Prot (8215s - canonical only), and Swiss-Prot with isoforms (9878s). As expected, differences prevail as a result of using different search databases. I compared this to an analysis done in Nov 2024 for a conference poster (ANS), which used identical search parameters except a slightly older Swiss-Prot with isoforms FASTA (9855s). Strangely, I could not replicate my results and got different significantly regulated proteins in MSstatsTMT (same parameters). Upon closer inspection, I noticed that the number of PSMs from the 2024 run was lower than 2025. For example…

  • 2024 - Swiss-Prot with isoforms FASTA (9855s) - 788953 PSMs identified across 96 raw files.

  • 2025 - Swiss-Prot with isoforms FASTA (9878s) - 768226 PSMs identified across 96 raw files.

  • Side Note: Yes, aware of caveats with using isoforms & challenges with protein grouping. Will likely stick to Swiss-Prot canonical only or Reference Proteome (1protein sequence per gene) for further analyses.

I was quite surprised because the new FASTA only had 23 more sequences, and the search method was the same. However, I remember that in the 2024 analysis was accidentally run with as a batch unchecked (forgot it was the opposite at the time) which produced one large .pdresults file (no run errors & all 96 raw files in PSM sheet). Whereas all the analyses in 2025 were run one by one (as File/as batch checked). Because of this, I decided to double-check to see whether the ‘as batch’ function affects the PSM results.

Using the exact same .pdstudy (processingWF + consensusWF + FASTAs), I re-ran a subset of 8 raw files, either with ‘as batch’ checked (by file/one by one) or ‘as batch’ unchecked (by batch/1 mega result file)

  • Note - raw files were input as File (not fractions) in PD2.4 (not that this should affect the PSMs…). Followed Enzo’s instructions from 2021/22.

    • Also note - I only care about the PSMs results as I export that from PD2.4 and pull into R for the protein Summarization & Statistical Analysis using MSstatsTMT in R.

Current Analysis

This finally brings me to the current analyses presented in this R script. Here, I run a quick analysis on the PSMs and MS/MS Spectrum Info outputs from PD2.4 analysis of those same 8 raw files.

Key

  • 2024 - e.g. PSMs_2024 or MSMS_2024

    • Data from the 8 raw files extracted from the large .pdresults file export produced by the PD2.4 analysis that submitted 96 files run as a batch (As batch unchecked). PD analysis submitted on 01 Nov 2024.

  • 2024_rrb - e.g. PSMs_2024_rrb or MSMS_2024_rrb

    • Here, those same 8 raw files were re–run as a batch of 8 (as batch unchecked) in PD2.4 with the exact same method. PD analysis submitted on 11 Sept 2025.

  • 2024_rro - e.g. PSMs_2024_rro or MSMS_2024_rro

    • Again, those same 8 raw files were re–run but one by one (as batch checked/by file) in PD2.4 with the exact same method. The individual .pdresults were exported & pulled in R, and appended together. PD analysis submitted on 11 Sept 2025.

  • 2025 - e.g. PSMs_2025 or MSMS_2025

    • The exported results from the 2025 runs of those 8 files were pulled in and appended together. This is similar to 2024_rro in the sense that all analyses here were submitted one by one (as batched checked/by file). However, this differs from the 3 2024 analyses above in the sense that it uses a slightly newer search database with 22 more sequences (see info above). Otherwise uses the exact same analysis method.

Skip to Part 3 - Email to Thermo (2025-09-22) for the key info!

Part 1 - Looking at Unique Annotated Sequences (PSMs)

Make combined df. Get unique sequences in each df. Then do barplot & then vennys

#https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/bind_rows.html
# bind_rows() .id alone doesn't work (just gives 1,2,3,4). need list & var name = df
cPSMs <- bind_rows(list(PSMs_2024 = PSMs_2024, 
                        PSMs_2024_rrb = PSMs_2024_rrb, 
                        PSMs_2024_rro = PSMs_2024_rro, 
                        PSMs_2025 = PSMs_2025),
                   .id = "df_id")

cPSMs_u_aseq

# https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/distinct.html
# get distinct/unique annotated sequences by df group
cPSMs_u_aseq <- cPSMs %>%
  group_by(df_id) %>% 
  distinct(`Annotated Sequence`)

# https://r-charts.com/color-palettes/

# plot no. of unique annotated seqeunces per df/group
cPSMs_u_aseq_plot <- cPSMs_u_aseq %>%
  group_by(df_id) %>%
  tally() %>%  # get tally of unique sequences by df for plot
  ggplot(aes(x = df_id, y = n, fill = df_id)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6, color = "grey10", alpha = .7) + 
  ylim(0,50000) + 
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(n)), # annotate count on graph
            vjust = -.2) +
  scale_fill_paletteer_d("ggthemes::excel_Organic") +
  labs(x = "PSM dataframe set (different PD analysis)",
       y = "no. of unique annotated sequences (n)",
       title = "Count of distinct annotated sequences in each PD PSM set (df_id)",
       subtitle = "Analysing as batch drops the no. of unique annotated sequences!",
       caption = "Each set has the SAME 8 LC-MS files! These are DEC2021_B1_TR1_F1-8.\n 
       PSMs_2024, PSMs_2024_rrb & PSMs_2024_rro all use the SAME FASTA & PD method! \n         The ONLY DIFFERENCE is that PSMs_2024 was analysed as batch (96 files submitted),
       PSMs_2024_rrb was analysed as batch (8 files submitted), while PSMs_2024_rro was submitted one by one (not as batch). \n 
       PSMs_2025 also submitted files one by one like PSMs_2024_rro & used the same PD method, but had a slightly newer SwissProt db (23 more seq).\n
       The mild increase between PSMs_2025 & PSMs_2024_rro of 75 seems reasonable for increasing the FASTA db by 23 sequences (although need to look at seq ID too in venny!). 
       However, the change between the other 3 based on running individually or by batch is bizzare. 
       The LC-MS raw files were input as files not fractions in PD & the PSMs table from PD shows PSMs by separate LCMS runs. So it should not be grouping it!
       Also the PD userguide does not indicate grouping PSMs (it groups at the peptide & protein grouping level!)
       Also the bizzare thing is that changing the no. of files submitted changes the no. of PSMs observed?!? ") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Vennys

# make venny function 
# see old folder in R_WD > thesis_dev > L&H2 > L&H2_LCMS_protein_counts_for_PhD_2025_v2
venny <- function(data, colors = NULL) {
  v <- ggvenn(data,
              digits = 0,
              stroke_alpha = 0.7,
              fill_alpha = 0.45,
              stroke_size = 0.5,
              set_name_size = 4,
              text_size = 3.5,
              fill_color = colors)
  }
# prep data
# map() function from purrr https://purrr.tidyverse.org/reference/map.html
#split_u_aseq <- split(cPSMs_u_aseq, f = cPSMs_u_aseq$df_id) # nvm 

lists_u_aseq <- cPSMs_u_aseq %>%
  split(.$df_id) %>% # split by df group
  map(~pull(., `Annotated Sequence`)) # makes mini func ~ to pull aseq & applies 2 all

Interim Summary (2025-09-12)

Overall, it seems that processing as batch (aka not clicking the as batch button on the analysis tab) drops the number of unique PSMs/annotated sequences compared to processing 1 by 1. And that the larger the number of files submitted as a batch are, the more the PSMs drop.

The PD 2.4 userguide is confusing & is the opposite of what they mean. The new PD 3.1 user guide has at least changed this button to ‘by file’ now, and somewhat gives more info on what it is doing in the search. Still why should processing as batch & increasing the number of files affect the PSMs identified? The separate spectrum file is retained in the PSM sheet. I thought batch affects the grouping level, e.g. (peptide groups to protein group sheets)?!?! Confused! -> CONT next week -> to email thermo.

~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~

              values_from = n) %>%
  rename(ID_precursor_0 = '0', # in quote otherwise does column order.
         ID_precursor_1 = '1') %>%
  mutate(no_precursors = ID_precursor_0 + ID_precursor_1)

  count(`Spectrum File`) %>%

Venn Diagrams showing similarities & differences of the unique annotated sequences across the analyses

All 4 PD analyses.

Interestingly, 2025 (run by file) is more similar to the 2024_rro (run by file) despite having a slightly larger/new FASTA file. The difference here seems expected given the slight difference in sequences form the 2024 vs 2025 FASTA. In contrast, the ones run as batch show fewer unique sequences.

  • See the Venn Diagram Panel in Part 1 for a clearer view & other venn Diagrams.
v1

The 3 2024 analyses (shown in 2025_09_18 email).

This Venn diagram shows that the number of unique identified annotated sequences (PSMs) from the same 8 raw files differs depending on whether it was submitted as batch (2024) or by file (2024_rro) in PD2.4. And also based on the size of the batch submitted - 2024 - 96 files vs 2024_rrb - 8 files.

Note the analysis method and database were exactly the same for all.
